      3. Keep track of your belongings. Never leave your cell phone or wallet unattended, and keep your wallet in your front pocket.
    </li>
    <br>
    <li>
      4. Avoid walking alone on the streets at night.
    </li>
    <li>5. Never drink tap water. Always buy water from water bottles.</li>
    <li>
      6. Judge your restaurant options by the overall cleanliness of the building. Avoid food stands.
    </li>
    <li>
      7. Tipping is customary in every interaction you do(including bagging your groceries, guiding your car out of a parking spot). Tips are usually less than American tips.
    </li>
    <li>
      8. Learning a little bit of Spanish can go a long way. Check out this <a href="https://www.fluentu.com/blog/spanish/useful-spanish-travel-phrases-words/">link </a> for a few great Spanish phrases.
    </li>
    <li>9. Always bring layers. Mexico City is chilly in the morning, very warm in the afternoon and very chilly at night. It can rain at any minute as well. </li>
    <li>10. Avoid wearing shorts and sandals. Most Mexicans don't wear these because of the changes in temperature and it instantly labels you as a tourist. </li>
  </ul>
